<item>
            <title>[FELIX-471] FilterImpl.toString() does not add escape characters</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/FELIX-471</link>
                <project id="12310100" key="FELIX">Felix</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;FilterImpl.toString() is not a complete representation of the filter string that was used to create it: four characters ( &apos;(&apos;, &apos;)&apos;, &apos;/&apos; and &apos;*&apos; ) should be preceded by a &apos;\&apos; if they are to be used in a value.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example,&lt;br/&gt;
  new FilterImpl(&quot;(b=&amp;#40;*)&quot;).toString();&lt;br/&gt;
should return &apos;(b=&amp;#40;*)&apos;, but it returns &apos;(b=&lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/star_yellow.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&apos;. So, it can happen that a correct Filter f, when used in&lt;br/&gt;
  new FilterImpl(f.toString());&lt;br/&gt;
causes an InvalidSyntaxException.&lt;br/&gt;
(see &lt;a href=&quot;http://www2.osgi.org/javadoc/r4/org/osgi/framework/Filter.html#toString(&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www2.osgi.org/javadoc/r4/org/osgi/framework/Filter.html#toString(&lt;/a&gt;) for what toString() should do).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See the attached patch for a proposed solution.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
